## End of Life (EOL) & End of Service Life (EOSL)

Manufacturers eventually stop supporting their products. Understanding the difference between these two stages is critical for maintaining a secure environment.

### End of Life (EOL)

The manufacturer announces they will **stop selling** the product. Security patches and updates are still available during this period, but it serves as the first warning that support will eventually end.

**Action:** Begin planning for replacement. Do not wait until EOSL to start evaluating alternatives.

### End of Service Life (EOSL)

The manufacturer **stops providing security patches and updates** entirely. The device will never receive another fix, regardless of what vulnerabilities are discovered.

**Action:** Replace the device as soon as possible. Running EOSL equipment is an ongoing, unmitigated security risk.

```
[Product Released]
      |
      ▼
[Active Support — full patches and updates]
      |
      ▼
[EOL Announced — still supported, but no longer sold]  ← Begin replacement planning
      |
      ▼
[EOSL — no more patches, ever]  ← Replace immediately if possible
      |
      ▼
[Legacy / Unpatched — permanent vulnerability exposure]
```

### Paid Extended Support

Some manufacturers offer continued support past EOSL for an additional fee — often substantial. This option is typically not financially viable for most organizations and should not be relied upon as a long-term strategy.

